Talk in the sleep
Some children talk during the night.
I am not referring to those who wake up very excited to tell us something that happened to them the previous day, but to those children who speak are still asleep.
The first time it happens, at most you get scared, but actually it doesn't matter very much.
It is a benign alteration of defined sleep sleep.
It occurs with a certain frequency, especially in children and adolescents.
Certainly, most of you have told me that you have spoken in your sleep.
This phenomenon can occur in a very sporadic way (once in life, for example, associated with a high fever episode) or with a greater regularity (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the day after the child remembers nothing anymore.
There is no single reason to explain this phenomenon.
Sometimes episodes are related to other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night fears, night enuresis (making the sleeping pipe), or sleep-abublism, but not necessarily so.
As mentioned above, it can be associated with very high fever stages, stress situations or overcrowding.
In any case, it is a phenomenon not yet studied.
The intensity with which it appears is also extremely variable.
It may happen that the person speaks with a very quiet tone of voice, with loose words, almost in a whisper, or that the opposite happens ( urla, cry, long speeches ...).
In cases where the event is particularly intense, you might need to observe the child and possibly consult a specialist to see if there are any issues that are generating an abnormal state of anxiety as a result of the situation.
We have said that this is a benign alteration, so there is no treatment unless it is associated with other sleep disorders that can be treated (e.g. when combined with insomnia or stress).
What can be done, however, is to take into account a series of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child too much before going to sleep.
Offer quiet games and avoid TV programs or series that cause fear or suggest violence.
With very nervous children for whom it is difficult to relax, relaxation techniques can be used to help them to gain some inner calm.
This will allow the child to sleep more quietly.
Once the dreamers appear to try to keep calm.
