Meeting - Blood is again safe
Hema-Québec celebrated yesterday the tenth anniversary of its foundation, and its president, Dr. FrancineDécary, had every reason to rejoice, since Hema-Québec became one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, it has regained public confidence, seriously broken by the scandal of infected blood between 1980 and 1990.
As we know, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were infected by the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C in the 1980s.
In the face of such a drama and the protests of the population, the Government of Canada conducted a public investigation in February 1994 , led by Judge Horace Krever , which aimed to highlight the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to disseminate recommendations to prevent a similar disaster.
While the judge Krever was delaying a report, some provinces set up a committee with the aim of designing a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, this mandate was carried out by the Gélineau Committee.
Following the reports of Gélineau et Krever, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to provide the Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society (Canadian Blood Society) for all other provinces and territories.
In 1998, when Hema-Québec started its activities, as 38% of the people said they still had confidence in the system of donations in Quebec, Dr. Décary recalled.
The situation was deadly.
Thanks to the continued efforts to improve the safety of blood transfusions and the field research over the years, we have regained public confidence," he explains before saying proudly that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of Quebec's population now had confidence in Hema-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary is convinced that "trust is something extremely fragile".
Since its creation on 28 September 1998, Hema-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At the time, there were many cases in Europe of the human variant of the crazy cow, a new manifestation of the disease of Creutzfeldt-Jakob, who told the president of it since 1998, the year of the foundation.
"And we didn't know at all if that disease could be transmitted through infected blood.
It is therefore based on one of the main recommendations of Krever and Gélinau's reports, according to which when you have doubts and you might get a serious illness, in this case the softness of Creutzfeldt-Jakob, which manifests itself with a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, are taken of exclusion measures.
In April 1999, the blood of those who had spent more than one month in the United Kingdom was rejected from 1980.
Now, for a few years, it has been shown that this disease has undoubtedly been transmitted through infected blood.
This episode so proved to us that it made sense to apply the precautionary principle."
In 1999 a much more efficient technique for the identification of HIV appeared on the market: nuclear acid (TAN) tests that allowed donors to directly recognise the presence of the virus in the blood and not the presence of antibodies against it, on which the tests used until then were based.
The TANs have allowed the window period to be reduced, i.e. since the person contracted the disease to the extent that the first viruses can be detected in the blood thanks to our techniques, explains the specialist.
That period could be reduced to less than one week.
The risk of ignoring the presence of infected donors and not being able to identify them is thus significantly reduced.
These improvements have resulted in a considerable reduction in the risk of AIDS being countered by a blood transfusion.
Today, a person of 12 million runs the risk of receiving blood infected from the HIV virus.
"In other words, this means that it will be necessary to distribute 12 million blood samples before someone is infected by the HIV virus.
Since Hema-Québec distributes between 400 000 and 500 000 blood samples each year, there will be more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmitted with a transfusion is found.
I believe that today you can feel calm in receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover health, says the head of the Hema-Quebec.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen will emerge in the system.
Not later than a year ago, the Chikungunya virus appeared on Réunion Island, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted to the blood by an insect.
Hema-Quebec must also provide sufficient resources, and must be constantly vigilant," continues Dr. Décary.
"The needs increase because the population is ageing.
Being the most aggressive cancer cures, patients often need a dose of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has consequences on the number of donors, which on average is only 3% of the inhabitants of Québec acceptable as donors."
However, all healthy people who are 18 years old and who meet the eligibility criteria can give blood every 56 days, that is, six times a year.
On average, 14% of those offering themselves as donors are not accepted because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have travelled to a country where the latter is disseminated, they will be rejected for a period equal to one year.
"With this 3% we manage to maintain an inventory capable of meeting the needs of hospitals.
The cases of poverty are very rare.
But it is necessary to renew the members of this group of donors as they age and cannot make any more donations.
It is now difficult to convince people to give blood, but above all to keep it and to encourage them to become regular donors.
Today's life is so frenzy that you find it difficult to give blood an hour," says desolate Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Québec not only distributes blood samples, but also human tissues, including bone trappings, eyeball valves and skin that are used almost exclusively for severe rashes.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being deposited at Hema-Québec that manages the only public bank of the blood of umbilical cordon in Quebec.
In the umbilical cord, which once was considered a biomedical discharge, there is plenty of blood rich in stem cells that can serve to cure serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the insertion into the bank of our thousandth blood sample of cordon and we expect to take more than a thousand each year.
It should begin to propose them for trappers at the beginning of next year," says Dr. Décary, who describes this blood take practice as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that you cannot have access," because Hema-Québec does not have the necessary means to propose this complex and costly program in all Québec hospitals.
