The psychology of excessive bidding: why spend more money?
Buyers are willing to spend more, to overestimate the goods.
Neurologists and economists researchers at the University of New York have been able to discover the neuro-economic bases of this well-known and apparently irrational behavior.
According to their study published on Science magazine, men do not want to stay behind in a competition such as the eBay auction, so they are available to pay even a higher price.
The research has tried to trace the nervous scheme of this "lot" at the level of the nervous system through experimental axes.
One group of volunteers played the game, the other group of players participated in an auction, while the functional magnetic resonance method (fMRI) examined the active areas of the brain of the participants in the experiment.
In both games participants could win money, but in the game of auction, in which the essential element is to bid more than the other, the body stretched under the brain cortex becomes intensely functioning when you lose the game.
This brain area, in addition to other functions, plays a role in the "self-gratification" mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to researchers, the rise in price is explained by scanning the actual reaction of the stretched body.
In support of their theory, the research group economists conducted a financial investigation.
In this investigation, three groups appealed against a partner under different conditions.
The control group reported the actual value of the product concerned and made their point.
To another group, they promised that in the event of a win, they would receive another $15 prize.
The third group would have received 15 dollars before the auction, but the members of the group would have lost the money in the event of a loss at the auction.
The difference between the two groups consisted in the fact that for one of them the gain was underlined, and for the other the loss.
Checking the hypothesis of neurologists the group members who were playing "against loss" were willing to make higher points of the control group or "winner".
"These results are not deductible from any of the previously existing economic theories.
In fact, these so far explained the phenomena that are responsive to auctions with the joy of winning and avoiding the risk.
Only the methods of creating the neurological image have helped resolve the contradiction between the two theories, so that we have come to a third explanation" - said Andrew Scotter, professor of the Faculty of Economics of the University of New York.
Hepatitis: when should you talk to your doctor?
Almost half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, but chronic liver diseases are mentioned in Hungary among the first causes of death.
In Hungary, the number of hepatitis patients goes up to 100 thousand, of which only 7000 are treated: the reason is that many patients do not know how to be infected.
The liver definition is the collective name of the infectious liver diseases caused by various viruses.
There are many similarities between symptoms, typical are hepatitis and itteracy, but their pathogen agents and the diseases caused differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses spread in two main forms depending on the pathogen agent: hepatitis A and E through the food channel (e.g. water and infected foods), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal loss, saliva).
For those travelling it is useful to immunise against the A and B virus, against the C no vaccine exists.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating infected foods, accompanied by general malaise, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After forming yellow spots on the skin and on the white of the eyes, the faeces become clear and the dark urine, the healing takes place within two or three weeks.
A million people die every year worldwide for hepatitis B, the most serious variant of the disease, causing liver tumors and liver cirrhosis.
The main reason, according to estimates, is that only one person in ten receives pharmacological treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if it is not treated it can cause liver cirrhosis and liver tumours.
Most infected people do not know that they have contracted the disease because the pathogens destroy the liver cells in a subtle way, in many cases the first symptoms occur 20-30 years later.
Therefore, it is very important to prevent and carry out regular medical tests.
This disease is much more frequent than the average in three groups: those who had a blood transfusion before 1991, the drug addicts and the tattoos.
In the world today, the number of people infected by chronic hepatitis C virus amounts to 200 million.
Because also a routine laboratory examination reveals the disease is worth addressing the family doctor when any unknown symptoms are observed.
Recognized in time the disease is curable, the virus can be eliminated from the body, thus stopping the infectious power and can prevent the formation of tumors.
On September 30, it is the world's day of hepatitis, organized for the first time in 2004 worldwide by associations of patients.
The aim is to draw attention to chronic hepatitis, to the causes of its development and early recognition of the disease.
Who believes in God feel less pain?
According to a recent survey, religious faith works as a kind of analgesic that has made the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
Scientists at Oxford University have had an interesting experience, examining how faith in God affects the feeling of pain, the British Telegraph reported.
In the somewhat bizarre investigation, an electroshock was performed to 12 Catholic believers and to other atheists, while all who observed a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
Based on the results, Catholic believers were able to reject much of the pain.
Thanks to the exploration technique of the human brain, it was discovered that Catholics were able to activate the part of the brain responsible for controlling the pain.
The test is the first of a series of research in which scientists, philosophers and theologians of the University also take part, as well as academics.
The test took place exactly like this: an instrument that emits discharges and passes the electroshock was connected to the left hand of the subject of the experiment.
The researchers asked the participants to focus on two paintings, the Virgin Mary painted in the 17th century by Sassoferrat and the Lady with Leonardo da Vinci hermelin painted in the 15th century.
The authors of the examination hoped that the image of the Virgin Mary originated a sort of religious status among the believers, while the Leonardo framework was chosen because it did not differ too much from the other and considered it to be a calming effect.
The subjects of the experiment spent half an hour in front of the MRI scanner and in this era of time received 20 electroshocks in four consecutive series, while observing either the painting on a religious theme or the other.
The Catholics reported that the Virgin Mary's vision made them feel "secure", as if "someone would take care of them" and "they were calmed and were overcome by peace".
Looking at the religious theme image, they account for 12% less pain than when they had before themselves the work of Leonardo.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who took part in the test himself, believes that such a result can be achieved with any image of the strong effect even for atheists, but you need to find the right image.
"We need to look for an image to which they nurture very positive feelings, such as a mother or a father," said the psychologist.
